1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:06,320
If you want to start trading or get back to 
what actually works, master this strategy.  

2
00:00:06,320 --> 00:00:13,120
It's built for beginners, but every profitable 
trader uses these exact principles. Here's the  

3
00:00:13,120 --> 00:00:15,840
foundation everyone needs. The Language 
of Price: Internalizing Market Structure 

4
00:00:15,840 --> 00:00:21,440
I used to be one of those traders with a 
Christmas tree chart – 10 different indicators,  

5
00:00:21,440 --> 00:00:26,720
all blinking and beeping like a damn 
casino. I thought I was a genius... 

6
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:32,000
But here's the brutal truth: all those 
indicators are just fancy ways to lose  

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:38,000
money faster. The only thing that matters 
is learning to read the market's language. 

8
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:43,920
This is called market structure and it's 
built on one simple thing: swing points. 

9
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:48,480
These are the obvious highs and 
lows price makes as it moves. 

10
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:54,000
A swing high is a candle that's higher 
than the candles on both sides of it. 

11
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,000
A swing low is lower than the nearby candles. 

12
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:04,160
Now, in an uptrend, the market makes a 
series of higher highs and higher lows. 

13
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:08,560
In a downtrend, it makes 
lower lows and lower highs. 

14
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:14,480
These are the building blocks of everything.
And these swing points aren't random. They're  

15
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:20,320
the market's way of telling you who's in 
control and when that control is shifting. 

16
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:24,560
Let me show you the two most 
important concepts you need to know. 

17
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:29,520
First is the Break of Structure. This 
is when price breaks a previous swing  

18
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:36,720
high in an uptrend. It's the market's way of 
saying "the trend is still alive and kicking." 

19
00:01:36,720 --> 00:01:43,440
Second is the Change of Character. This is when 
price breaks the last major swing low in an  

20
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:49,680
uptrend. It's the market's first warning 
sign that the trend might be in trouble. 

21
00:01:49,680 --> 00:01:55,040
Watch this. We're in a clear uptrend, 
making higher swing highs and higher  

22
00:01:55,040 --> 00:02:00,720
swing lows. Each time price makes a new 
high, that's a Break of Structure —a  

23
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:07,440
confirmation that buyers are still in control.
But look what happens here. Price makes a sharp  

24
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:14,160
move down and breaks below the last swing low. 
That's a Change of Character. The market just told  

25
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:19,360
you that the trend structure is cracked.
This doesn't mean the trend is over,  

26
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:24,800
but it means you need to be careful. The 
character of the market just changed from  

27
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:31,600
strong bullish momentum to potential weakness.
Here's the key insight: You want to trade with  

28
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:36,000
the structure, not against it.
In a trending market with clean  

29
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:41,360
Break of Structure patterns, you look for 
entries in the direction of the trend. 

30
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:47,840
But when you start seeing Change of Character 
patterns, you either take profits or step aside. 

31
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:51,600
This is how you read the market's 
intentions while everyone else is  

32
00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:58,673
guessing. Most traders spend months figuring 
this out. You just learned it in 2 minutes.

33
00:02:58,673 --> 00:03:02,000
Context is King: Are You in a Trend or a Range?
Okay, so you can read basic structure. Now,  

34
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:08,160
let me show you the most important decision you 
must make before even thinking about a trade.  

35
00:03:08,160 --> 00:03:14,480
You have to identify the overall market state.
Before you even think about entering a trade,  

36
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:20,000
you must answer one simple question: 
Are you in a trend or a range? 

37
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,960
This is the most important first decision 
you'll make. Because different strategies  

38
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:32,240
apply to trending markets versus ranging markets.
So how do you tell the difference? Here's the  

39
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:38,480
dead-simple method that works every time.
Add a single moving average to your chart,  

40
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:45,200
the 50 EMA. When price is above this 
line, you have an uptrend bias. When  

41
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:52,800
price is below, you have a downtrend bias.
But what about ranges? Watch this. The 50 EMA will  

42
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:59,760
be flat, and price will be chopping around it.
Here's what most traders get wrong. They try  

43
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:05,200
to force trades in every market condition.
But the professional waits for the right  

44
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:09,920
context. If you're in a strong 
uptrend, you look for dips to buy. 

45
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:14,320
If you're in a range, you look 
for bounces off the boundaries. 

46
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:20,922
This single concept will save you more 
money than any fancy indicator ever will.

47
00:04:20,922 --> 00:04:23,920
Chart Setup for Clarity, Not Confusion
Look at this chaos. Most beginner traders  

48
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:30,480
have charts that look like this. Ten indicators, 
five different timeframes open at once,  

49
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:37,280
and they wonder why they can't make a decision.
Most traders get wrong about chart setup. They  

50
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:45,040
think more information equals better decisions. 
But in trading, you need clarity, not confusion. 

51
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:49,040
Your chart has one job: to 
help you execute trades,  

52
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:55,440
not to analyze the entire market. So we're going 
to strip everything down to the essentials. 

53
00:04:55,440 --> 00:05:00,160
First, pick one market. I don't 
care if it's euro dollar, Tesla,  

54
00:05:00,160 --> 00:05:07,600
or Bitcoin. Pick one and stick with it for your 
next 100 days. You need to learn how that one  

55
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:15,200
market moves before you start jumping around.
Next, you need exactly two timeframes. Not five,  

56
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:22,400
not ten. Two. The 1-hour chart for 
structure and the 5-minute chart for entry.  

57
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:28,880
The 1-hour tells you the big picture. The 
5-minute tells you when to pull the trigger. 

58
00:05:28,880 --> 00:05:34,560
Now, for indicators, you get one, 
for now... The 50 EMA. That's it.  

59
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:40,880
This line will show you trend direction.
The goal is to see price action clearly.  

60
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:46,747
Price is the only thing that pays 
you. Everything else is just noise.

61
00:05:46,747 --> 00:05:46,800
The Only Two Levels That 
Matter: Support & Resistance 

62
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:53,520
Here's a question that will make you rich or keep 
you broke: where do trades actually happen? Well,  

63
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:58,720
they happen at specific price levels.
At support and resistance. These are  

64
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:04,560
the only levels where the market actually 
gives a damn. Everything else is noise. 

65
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:09,520
And here's where 90% of traders 
completely lose their minds. 

66
00:06:09,520 --> 00:06:16,320
They start drawing lines everywhere. A line 
here, one there, trendlines going in every  

67
00:06:16,320 --> 00:06:22,960
direction like a spider web designed by a madman.
Remember this like your trading life depends  

68
00:06:22,960 --> 00:06:30,880
on it: the market only cares about two types 
of levels: real support and real resistance. 

69
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:35,520
First, forget everything you know 
about drawing lines. These levels  

70
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:42,560
aren't thin lines—they're zones. Areas 
where price has repeatedly shown interest. 

71
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:49,920
Look at this level. Price has touched it 2 times. 
Each time, it bounced off this area. That's a  

72
00:06:49,920 --> 00:06:57,200
support zone. It's not a single price point—it's 
a range of prices where buyers keep showing up. 

73
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:02,720
But here's the part no one explains. Not 
all support and resistance zones are created  

74
00:07:02,720 --> 00:07:08,880
equal. You need to understand the difference 
between "fresh" zones and "tested" zones. 

75
00:07:08,880 --> 00:07:15,120
A fresh zone is one that hasn't been 
revisited since it was created. These zones  

76
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:21,120
often provide the strongest reactions.
A tested zone is one that's been hit  

77
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:26,640
multiple times. Each time it gets 
tested, it gets a little weaker. 

78
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:32,640
Most traders keep trading the same tested 
levels over and over, wondering why they're  

79
00:07:32,640 --> 00:07:38,800
not working anymore. You need to hunt for the 
fresh zones that haven't been discovered yet. 

80
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:44,720
And there's one more concept that changes 
everything. Role reversal. When a strong support  

81
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:51,760
level finally breaks, it doesn't just disappear. 
It becomes a powerful new resistance level. 

82
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:58,240
Watch this happen. We had a major support 
zone. Price kept bouncing off it. Then,  

83
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:04,480
it breaks through with force. Now watch what 
happens when price comes back to test that  

84
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:11,360
same level from below. Rejection! The old 
support is now acting as new resistance. 

85
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:14,080
Just by understanding these simple concepts,  

86
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:18,515
you've already put yourself 
ahead of 90% of traders.

87
00:08:18,515 --> 00:08:20,880
Spotting the Traps - Liquidity and Inducement
Now I'm going to teach you something that most  

88
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:28,240
traders learn too late. The market is designed to 
take your money. It's not personal—it's business.  

89
00:08:28,240 --> 00:08:33,520
And the way it takes your money is 
through liquidity hunting and inducement. 

90
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:39,920
Let me ask you something. Where do you think 
most traders put their stop-losses? Above obvious  

91
00:08:39,920 --> 00:08:47,040
highs and below obvious lows, right? That's 
exactly what big market players is counting on. 

92
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:54,880
These areas where stop-losses cluster are called 
liquidity. And smart money hunt this liquidity. 

93
00:08:54,880 --> 00:09:01,440
Here's how it works. You see a resistance area. 
It looks like a perfect short opportunity.  

94
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:08,080
Where do you put your stop-loss? Above the 
highs, of course. So does everyone else. 

95
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:13,920
But smart money sees this differently. They 
see all those stop-losses sitting above the  

96
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:21,120
highs as an opportunity. They push price up to 
trigger all those stops, collect the liquidity,  

97
00:09:21,120 --> 00:09:25,600
and then dump the market hard.
This is called inducement.  

98
00:09:25,600 --> 00:09:29,760
The market creates a seemingly 
perfect setup to lure you in,  

99
00:09:29,760 --> 00:09:36,160
then traps you before making the real move.
Most beginners see this happen and think they  

100
00:09:36,160 --> 00:09:42,000
just got unlucky. But you're different, you’re 
going to see it as a predictable pattern. 

101
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:48,240
Here's the question that will save you thousands 
of dollars: Where is the obvious trade? And where  

102
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:54,320
would the stops for that trade be? Because 
that's where the market will likely go next. 

103
00:09:54,320 --> 00:10:00,000
Let me show you this in action. We have a 
perfect-looking support level. Most traders  

104
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:07,120
see this and think "great, I'll buy the bounce and 
put my stop below the low." But smart money sees  

105
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:13,200
all those stops below the low as a target.
Watch what happens. Price comes down to  

106
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:18,240
the support level, breaks through it 
just enough to trigger all the stops,  

107
00:10:18,240 --> 00:10:25,200
and then immediately reverses back up. They 
hunted the liquidity and then made the real move. 

108
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:31,360
This is why most traders get stopped out right 
before the move goes in their favor. They're  

109
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:39,233
not unlucky—they're predictable. And in trading, 
predictable equals profitable... for someone else.

110
00:10:39,233 --> 00:10:42,800
High-Probability Zones: The Power of Confluence
Now we start building. The foundation is laid.  

111
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:49,440
Let me show you how to find an A+ trading 
location. This is a concept called confluence,  

112
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:57,360
where multiple factors align to signal a powerful 
opportunity. Most traders are one-dimensional.  

113
00:10:57,360 --> 00:11:04,320
They see a support level and they buy. That’s 
it. They trade one reason and hope it works. 

114
00:11:04,320 --> 00:11:08,880
The smart approach is to wait for 
multiple, independent reasons to  

115
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:14,000
align at the same place and time.
Here's your first confluence model,  

116
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:18,240
and it's going to be the backbone 
of your entire trading approach.  

117
00:11:18,240 --> 00:11:23,920
You need your higher timeframe trend 
plus a key support or resistance zone. 

118
00:11:23,920 --> 00:11:30,560
Let me show you exactly what this looks like. 
On the 1-hour chart, we're in a clear uptrend.  

119
00:11:30,560 --> 00:11:38,960
Price is above the 50-EMA, making higher highs 
and higher lows. That's your directional bias. 

120
00:11:38,960 --> 00:11:44,160
Now, price is pulling back to a 
major support zone. But this isn't  

121
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:51,520
just any support zone—it's one that used to be 
resistance. Remember the role reversal concept. 

122
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:58,160
So you have a higher timeframe uptrend meeting 
a key structural level. This is confluence,  

123
00:11:58,160 --> 00:12:03,840
and it's where you start paying attention.
But here's the key—this confluence doesn't  

124
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:09,920
mean you trade yet. That's amateur hour.
Professionals use confluence to narrow  

125
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:14,480
down where they want to trade, 
then they wait for confirmation. 

126
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:19,280
This is the difference between hoping 
and knowing. You're not hoping the level  

127
00:12:19,280 --> 00:12:24,000
holds—you're waiting for the market 
to show you that it's going to hold. 

128
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:30,365
That's one of the three key pillars of this 
entire system. And we're just getting started.

129
00:12:30,365 --> 00:12:32,320
The VWAP Magnet - Your Entry Anchor
Now let me show you a weapon that  

130
00:12:32,320 --> 00:12:38,960
institutional traders use as a daily benchmark.
It's called the Volume Weighted Average Price,  

131
00:12:38,960 --> 00:12:43,680
or VWAP and it's the true mean 
price for the day, weighted by  

132
00:12:43,680 --> 00:12:50,400
volume—like the market's center of gravity.
Here's why this matters. When institutional  

133
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:57,680
traders want to buy or sell large positions, 
they use VWAP as their benchmark. They try to  

134
00:12:57,680 --> 00:13:05,200
buy below VWAP and sell above VWAP. This 
makes VWAP act like a magnet for price. 

135
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:11,680
So let me show you how to use this. Add VWAP 
to your 5-minute chart. You'll see it as a  

136
00:13:11,680 --> 00:13:18,560
dynamic line that moves with price, but it's 
much more responsive than a moving average. 

137
00:13:18,560 --> 00:13:24,320
Watch how price behaves around it. In a 
trending market, price will pull back to  

138
00:13:24,320 --> 00:13:32,000
this line. It touches the VWAP, bounces off it, 
and continues in the direction of the trend. 

139
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:37,680
This is your entry anchor. Remember that 
confluence zone we found? When price  

140
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:42,880
pulls back to that zone, you're not just 
looking for any entry. You're looking for  

141
00:13:42,880 --> 00:13:49,680
a specific test of the VWAP within that zone.
This is how you turn a good setup into a great  

142
00:13:49,680 --> 00:13:56,720
setup. You have your higher timeframe trend, your 
key structural level, and now your institutional  

143
00:13:56,720 --> 00:14:03,040
benchmark all lining up in one place.
So the absolute A+ setup is when the  

144
00:14:03,040 --> 00:14:10,960
1-Hour trend is up, price has pulled back into a 
1-Hour support zone, and on the 5-minute chart,  

145
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:18,480
that pullback is now touching the VWAP line.
This VWAP test is the anchor for our entire  

146
00:14:18,480 --> 00:14:24,160
trade idea. It's the precise point 
of interest within our broader zone. 

147
00:14:24,160 --> 00:14:29,840
But remember, this VWAP test is the 
anchor, but it's not the entry signal. 

148
00:14:29,840 --> 00:14:35,280
The signal is a specific candle pattern 
that confirms buyers are actually stepping  

149
00:14:35,280 --> 00:14:41,328
in right here, and I'll show you exactly 
what that looks like in just a moment.

150
00:14:41,328 --> 00:14:43,680
The Entry Myth: Setup vs. Signal
First, let's talk about a critical  

151
00:14:43,680 --> 00:14:48,720
distinction that trips up almost every 
beginner. You see the price come down  

152
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:55,440
to your perfect level—the 1-Hour support 
zone, the 5-minute VWAP test. Everything  

153
00:14:55,440 --> 00:15:02,400
is aligned. The problem is, the amateur 
trader gets excited and buys immediately.  

154
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:08,720
They're buying at a location, hoping it holds.
But imagine if you waited for one final piece  

155
00:15:08,720 --> 00:15:14,800
of evidence, a confirmation that buyers 
are actually present and fighting back. 

156
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:19,280
The result is you would filter out 
so many failed trades where the  

157
00:15:19,280 --> 00:15:25,040
price just slices right through the level.
This is the difference between a "setup" and  

158
00:15:25,040 --> 00:15:31,920
a "signal." The setup is the context. It's the 
high-probability condition we've just defined:  

159
00:15:31,920 --> 00:15:38,960
a pullback to the VWAP that happens inside a key 
higher-timeframe support zone, all while the main  

160
00:15:38,960 --> 00:15:45,600
trend is up. The setup tells you where to look.
The "signal" is the specific event on your  

161
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:52,320
5-minute chart that tells you when to act. It's 
the proof. It’s the footprint of buyers stepping  

162
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:59,760
in and dominating sellers at that exact spot.
The professional waits for this perfect alignment.  

163
00:15:59,760 --> 00:16:04,720
The amateur buys the location and hopes.
You now understand the difference  

164
00:16:04,720 --> 00:16:10,480
between a location and a reason. Most 
traders never learn this distinction.

165
00:16:10,480 --> 00:16:12,960
The Outside Candle - Your Go-To Signal
Now I'm going to give you the most  

166
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:18,480
reliable entry signal in your entire 
arsenal. It's called the outside candle,  

167
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:22,880
and it's the market's way of screaming 
that the momentum has shifted. 

168
00:16:22,880 --> 00:16:28,400
A bullish outside candle is a large green 
candle that completely swallows the body  

169
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:35,120
of the previous red candle. It's the market’s 
way of saying that buyers are now in control. 

170
00:16:35,120 --> 00:16:40,320
A bearish outside candle is a large 
red candle that engulfs the body of  

171
00:16:40,320 --> 00:16:46,080
the previous green candle. It means 
sellers just took over with force. 

172
00:16:46,080 --> 00:16:51,120
But here's the critical part. This 
candle pattern is only valid when it  

173
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:58,240
shows at your VWAP test. An outside candle 
in the middle of nowhere is meaningless. 

174
00:16:58,240 --> 00:17:04,880
Let me show you this in action. We have 
our perfect setup: uptrend on the 1-hour,  

175
00:17:04,880 --> 00:17:11,200
pullback to a key support zone, and 
price testing VWAP. Now we wait. 

176
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:17,520
Watch what happens here. This candle 
completely engulfs the previous candle's body. 

177
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:22,800
That's your signal. The market just told 
you that buyers stepped in with force at  

178
00:17:22,800 --> 00:17:30,560
the VWAP level. This isn't hope—this is evidence.
And the size of the outside candle tells you how  

179
00:17:30,560 --> 00:17:38,400
strong the momentum shift is. A large candle with 
high volume is like the market screaming. A small  

180
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:43,600
candle is like the market whispering.
You want the market to be screaming  

181
00:17:43,600 --> 00:17:49,920
when you enter a trade. You want that 
outside candle to be large, decisive. 

182
00:17:49,920 --> 00:17:57,797
This is your go-to entry signal. It's simple, it's 
reliable, and it works in all market conditions.

183
00:17:57,797 --> 00:18:00,400
Fibonacci Precision - Layering Your Targets
Now I'm going to show you how to add a third  

184
00:18:00,400 --> 00:18:06,480
layer of confluence to your system. We're going 
to use Fibonacci retracements and extensions  

185
00:18:06,480 --> 00:18:12,800
to find precision entry and exit points.
The Fibonacci retracement tool helps you  

186
00:18:12,800 --> 00:18:20,880
identify where pullbacks are likely to end. The 
most important levels are the 61.8% retracement,  

187
00:18:20,880 --> 00:18:25,920
also known as the "golden pocket."
When your VWAP test also lines up  

188
00:18:25,920 --> 00:18:33,280
with the 61.8% Fibonacci level, you have 
triple confluence. Trend direction, VWAP,  

189
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:40,400
and Fibonacci all pointing to the same level.
And here's where it gets really powerful. You  

190
00:18:40,400 --> 00:18:48,400
can use Fibonacci extensions to set logical profit 
targets. The 1 61 and 2 61 extension levels are  

191
00:18:48,400 --> 00:18:55,360
where institutional traders often take profits.
Let me show you this system in action. We have  

192
00:18:55,360 --> 00:19:02,800
